definition.value: The D-stereoisomer of  sorbofuranose.
A D-sorbofuranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric center.
A D-sorbofuranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric center.
The D-stereoisomer of sorbopyranose.
A D-sorbopyranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric center.
A D-sorbopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric center.
The pyranose form of sorbose.
Any member of the class of naphthalenes in which the naphthalene ring is directly attached to the carbonyl carbon of a carboxamide group.

An ethylenediamine derivative that is ethane-1,2-diamine in which one hydrogen attached to each of the nitrogens is sutstituted by a 1-hydroxybutan-2-yl group (S,S-configuration). It is a bacteriostatic antimycobacterial drug, effective against Mycobacterium tuberculosis and some other mycobacteria. It is used (as the dihydrochloride salt) in combination with other antituberculous drugs in the treatment of pulmonary and extrapulmonary tuberculosis; resistant strains of M. tuberculosis are readily produced if ethambutol is used alone.
Salts of selenous acid.
An inorganic sodium salt composed of sodium and selenite ions in a 2:1 ratio.
Semisynthetic derivative of erythromycin A.
Any fatty acid containing a ring composed of atoms including at least one heteroatom.
A bilin that consists of 8,12-bis(2-carboxyethyl)-18-ethyl-3-ethylidene-2,7,13,17-tetramethyl-2,3-dihydrobilin bearing two oxo substituents at positions 1 and 19.
A thiazolidine or thiazolidine derivative carrying a single carboxy substituent.
An azole in which the five-membered heterocyclic aromatic skeleton contains a N atom and one S atom.
Any of several wide-spectrum macrolide antibiotics obtained from actinomycete Saccharopolyspora erythraea (formerly known as Streptomyces erythraeus).
Any L-alpha-amino acid carrying an N-acyl substituent.
A tartaric acid anion that is the conjugate base of 2,3-dihydroxybutanedioic acid.
A major geometrical isomer of roxithromycin.
A branched-chain saturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of isovaleric acid; reported to improve ruminal fermentation and feed digestion in cattle.
A branched, short-chain, saturated fatty acid anion; the conjugate base of isobutyric acid, formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group.
A primary alcohol that is  isopentane substituted by a hydroxy group at position 1.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 4-hydroxyphenylacetic acid.
A primary alcohol that is ethanol substituted by a phenyl group at position 2.
A  hydroxycoumarin that is umbelliferone in which the hydrogen at position 6 is substituted by a hydroxy group. It is used in filters for absorption of ultraviolet light.
